{{Quote|This product was packed under strict quality control on the system Amorphiia ''[sic]'', and this instruction cassette provided by the manufacturer. It offers a unique chance for consumers everywhere to meet an Amorphiian being.|Instruction cassette announcer|<ref name="SWHS" />}}
The '''Amorphiians''', or '''Amorphiian beings''', were a [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] [[Species/Legends|species]] indigenous to the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Amorphiia]] in the [[Mid Rim/Legends|Mid Rim]]. Although they appeared identical to baseline [[Human/Legends|Humans]], the Amorphiians' motor abilities suffered frequent power fluctuations, causing them to speed up, slow down, or gyrate wildly, depending on the nature of a particular malfunction. Amorphiians had the ability to restore normal functionality to a limp or uncooperative body structure by rubbing, pushing, moving, or otherwise stimulating the body part.

At least one [[Unidentified Amorphiian company|Amorphiian company]] was selling a brand of [[mini-transmitter]] in [[1 ABY/Legends|1 ABY]]. The model shipped with an [[instruction cassette]] hosted by an Amorphiian named [[Dromboid]]. The recording's opening announcement touted the cassette as a unique chance for consumers in [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] to meet an Amorphiian being. Nevertheless, the manufacturer was careful to note that the Amorphiians' propensity for power glitches was in no way a reflection on the safety or utility of their product.

==Biology and appearance==
{{Quote|The motor abilities of Amorphiian citizens are frequently impaired by malfunctions, which result in a temporary loss of power. This in no way reflects on the safety of our product. Rather, it should serve as a guarantee of our high standard of long wear and durability.|Instruction cassette announcer|<ref name="SWHS" />}}
Amporhiians were a [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] [[Species/Legends|species]] of [[humanoid]],<ref name="CSWE I 29" /> pluri-interface [[Android/Legends|androids]].<ref name="SkyeWalkers" /> Also known as Amorphiian beings, they looked like standard [[Human/Legends|Humans]],<ref name="SWHS" /> with proportions and outward anatomy matching those of other [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] [[Humanoid/Legends|humanoid]] [[Species/Legends|species]].<ref name="CSWE I 29" /> At least one member of the species had [[Color/Legends|gray]] hair, blue [[Eye/Legends|eyes]], and pale skin. Amorphiians had [[Brain/Legends|neural]]-cranial synapses and the ability to feel pain.<ref name="SWHS" />

Amorphiians were distinguished from other species by their machine-like qualities. For example, an Amorphiian's movements were accompanied by a whirring noise. Members of the species also exhibited various quirks: an Amorphiian could beep or gesticulate rapidly in a localized area of the body, such as the chin, eyelids, fingers, neck, or tongue.<ref name="SWHS" /> Amorphiians experienced frequent problems with their neural motor systems.<ref name="CSWE I 29" /> This resulted in a lack of power to the body or a portion thereof, leading to slower, faster, or erratic movements. Such fluctuations caused the voice to vary in pitch and speed, the eyes to cross, or the body to sway oddly. Amorphiians dealt with these losses of power by stimulating a part of the body to restore normal functionality. For instance, a malfunctioning Amorphiian could return to normal by re-extending a limp finger, pressing on stalled hips, rubbing the forehead, flapping the [[Limb/Legends|arms]], or even using standard tools to tweak a stalled smile. On a total loss of power, an Amorphiian collapsed.<ref name="SWHS" />

==Society and culture==
{{Quote|Now find the circuit-breaker module. And, by the way, let's start calling these components by their proper names. 'Circuit-&hellip;breaker&hellip;module&hellip;'|Dromboid, hosting an instruction cassette|<ref name="SWHS" />}}
At least one [[Unidentified Amorphiian company|Amorphiian company]] sold [[mini-transmitter]]s outside the species' home, the [[Amorphiia system/Legends|Amorphiia system]]; the purpose of these items was to translate speech into one of 1,000 other [[Language/Legends|languages]]. The [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiee]] [[Lumpawaroo/Legends|Lumpawarrump]] owned one of these units on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Kashyyyk/Legends|Kashyyyk]] in [[1 ABY/Legends|1 ABY]].<ref name="SWHS" /><ref name="date">{{SWBoards|url=thread.jspa?threadID=152583&start=870#15778940|thread=Holocron continuity database questions|user=[[Leland Chee|Tasty Taste]]|date=2006-10-12|time=6:13 PM|quote=Wookiee Life Day occurs every 3 years, one of which fell at ~1.5 ABY.}}</ref> This mini-transmitter came with a bag of tools, a [[circuit-breaker module]], an [[impulse-to-voice translator]], and an [[instruction cassette]] to explain the assembly process.<ref name="SWHS" />

The announcement preceding the instructional cassette acknowledged the power fluctuations experienced by Amorphiians but insisted that these malfunctions did not affect the product itself. The disclaimer also insinuated that encountering an Amorphiian was a rare occasion for most members of the [[galactic community]]. The instruction video itself was hosted by a [[Gender/Legends|male]] Amorphiian named [[Dromboid]].<ref name="Dromboid">The article {{InsiderCite|106|I Have a Bad Feeling About This!}} uses the name "Dromboid" in conjunction with this character, but it does no specify whether it is the character's proper name or an alternative name for his species. However, the fourth draft script for ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]'', confirms that the character's name is in fact Dromboid.</ref> The host wore clothing standard for most other [[Realspace/Legends|spacefaring]] species: a [[shirt]], trousers, a jacket, and a belt. Dromboid was a fastidious representative of his species, speaking in an even and emotionless keel, yet purporting to appreciate beauty. Dromboid's instructions revealed, however, that the erratic nature of Amorphiians could be frustrating to members of other species.<ref name="SWHS" />

==History==
{{Quote|Thank you for selecting our brand of mini-transmitter. If you assemble it properly, following the instructions I am about to give you, it will provide many years of fun, and valuable service to you.|Dromboid, hosting an instruction cassette|<ref name="SWHS" />}}
The Amorphiians hailed from the planet [[Amorphiia]],<ref name="CSWE I 29" /> located in the Amorphiia [[Star system/Legends|system]] in the [[Eidoloni sector/Legends|Eidoloni sector]] of the [[Mid Rim/Legends|Mid Rim]].<ref name="TEAOC">{{SW|url=news/star-wars-the-essential-atlas-online-companion|text=''Star Wars: The Essential Atlas'' Online Companion|int=Star Wars: The Essential Atlas Online Companion}}</ref> Their region of [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] had been reached by outsiders sometime between [[3000 BBY|3000]] and [[1000 BBY/Legends|1000 BBY]]. The world remained in unaligned or contested space during the last few [[Standard year/Legends|years]] of the [[New Sith Wars]], from [[1004 BBY|1004]] to 1,000 BBY. By the [[Time/Legends|time]] of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], it was in [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] space.<ref name="TEA">''[[The Essential Atlas]]''</ref> In [[50 BBY/Legends|50 BBY]], a revolution broke out on [[Arkania/Legends|Arkania]] between the ruling [[Arkanian Dominion|Dominion]] government and the [[Arkanian/Legends|Arkanian]] [[Arkanian Renegades|Renegades]].<ref name="NEC">''[[The New Essential Chronology]]''</ref> [[Scientist/Legends|Scientists]] from the Dominion spliced Amorphiian [[DNA/Legends|genetic sequences]] with several other species to create ultimate warriors, known as [[Accelerated Transgenic Heuristic Abhorer]]s. The Abhorers were successful in defeating the insurrection and were subsequently destroyed by the Arkanians (bar [[Zeta Magnus|one]] who escaped destruction).<ref name="SkyeWalkers" />

By 1 ABY,<ref name="date" /> the Amorphiians had established a mini-transmitter industry, exporting their products beyond their home [[Star/Legends|star]] system along with instruction cassettes that touted the consumer's chance to meet a member of the Amorphiian species, albeit only virtually.<ref name="SWHS" /> The region of Amorphiia had a low average population density of between one and ten million inhabitants per system c. [[25 ABY/Legends|25 ABY]]. The planet was within territory controlled by [[Darth Krayt]] as part of his [[Darth Krayt's Galactic Empire|Galactic Empire]] by [[137 ABY]].<ref name="TEA" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|Harvey Korman, as Dromboid, appears on the screen, as a kind of Milton Cross/Bergen Evans instructor, who is guiding the youngster [''sic''] of the galaxy through the mysteries of electronics|''Star Wars Holiday Special'' script, fourth draft|<ref name="Draft4">{{WebCite|url=http://www.starwarsholidayspecial.com/text/script.htm|text=The Fourth Draft Script - 09/13/78|work=starwarsholidayspecial.com|archivedate=20180611081514}}</ref>}}
The Amorphiian named Dromboid appears in a short comedy segment in ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]'', which aired on television in [[1978]]. The character, portrayed by American comedian [[Harvey Korman]], teaches the young Wookiee Lumpy how to assemble a mini-transmitter. All the while, Dromboid's constant malfunctions frustrate the young Wookiee.<ref name="IHABFAT 32">{{InsiderCite|106|I Have a Bad Feeling About This!}}</ref> The fourth draft script of the special spells the species' name ''Amorphiian'',<ref name="SWHSs 109A">''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]'' script, 4th draft</ref> a spelling that is echoed as [[canon]]ical in ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]'', published in [[2008]].<ref name="CSWE I 29" />

